<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Slicer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I poked around a bit, and found what I believe to be the way Initative affects attack and recharge delays.<P>Let the players AggDef be -100 to 100, where -100 is max defense and +100 is max offense. All delays are calculated in 1/100 second.<P>ComputedAttackDelay=(weapon.attackdelay + 100) - (player.initiative(weapon.initiativeskill) * 0.5 * 0.333333);<BR>ComputedAttackDelay-=player.aggdef;<BR>if (ComputedAttackDelay &lt; 100.0)<BR>  ComputedAttackDelay=100.0;<P>ComputedRechargeDelay=(weapon.rechargedelay + 100) - (player.initative(weapon.initiativeskill) * 0.5 * 0.666666);<BR>ComputerRechargeDelay-=player.aggdef;<BR>if (ComputedRechargeDelay &lt; 100.0)<BR>  ComputedRechargeDelay=100.0;<P>In other words...<BR>Setting your aggdef to maximum subtracts one second from each of recharge and attack, setting it to it's minimum adds one to each.<BR>Having 600 in the initative skill will reduce attack speed by 1 second and recharge speed by 2 seconds.<BR>The effective attack delay and recharge delay can never be less than 1 second.<P>So at HIGH levels, you're probably better off going after weapons with high delays as your skills will offset them  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>Now, I don't know how the server does things, but this is how the client calculates how often you should shoot... Odds are the two are the same  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">segmy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">thanks for the info.<P>Mind telling me what is the key for .dat files is?  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>I am pretty sure its XOR, but I suck at breaking them anyways  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/frown.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">ElBigmac</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Have you been so far as to figure out how its affected by weilding two weapons (or weilding one or two and punching for MA)?<P>This is great stuff  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">casey</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">there was a post on another mb i read where a AO dev was interviewed on initiatives and attack/recharge speeds.  I'll try and dig it up and post it here.<P>One thing he mentioned that i remember offhand is that he stated the minimun atk and rechare was .5 seconds, not 1.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">casey</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">found it <BR> <A HREF="http://pub75.ezboard.com/fhakkinshousefrm5.showMessage?topicID=259.topic" TARGET=_blank>http://pub75.ezboard.com/fhakkinshousefrm5.showMessage?topicID=259.topic</A> <P>it doesnt talk about the aggdef slider directly, just the application of your initiative skills to the weapon atk and recharge, and says the aggdef slider increases the effect of them.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Schattendrachen</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Now, does this also apply to nanoformulas?<P>I've gotta know this, cause I'm a nanotech...  =)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Vehementi</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hold on... the explanation from devs in  the above URL directly contradicts what you said in your post... <P>You said yours was client side... and we all know that the server is b0rked when it comes to speed... maybe that is the difference<P>(time passes, I edit post numerous times due to my own stupidity and inability to read)<P>Yes, I think I'm right.  This is the client-side coding, and the client side obviously runs at real-time (one second = one second.)  The server however, runs at half speed, if you've timed it (half speed at the fastest!) so the Funcom person might have been talking about the server-side speed, while you're talking about the client-side speed.  This would make the data concur.  If the client waits 1 second for recharge speed, and the server waits 0.5 seconds (of its borked seconds), then in theory they'd be in sync, right?<P>-V<p>[This message has been edited by Vehementi (edited 08-17-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Blabaddy_Hoo</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Slicer,<P>Just last night i found a pistol/shotgun weapon that had an attack speed of 0.25 and a recharge speed of 0.70.<P>if attack and recharge speeds cannot be less than 1 second, then are the stats for that weapon actually atk=1.0s/rch=1.0s ?<P>this would be pretty useful information because it would mean that the weapon was basically a lot crappier than i though it was, because it had a damage of 1-6(122).<P>I had assumed that it had the ability to crit for 122 4 times a second, but under your explaination, it doesnt make any sense to have a weapon that only does 1-6 points of damage per second...<P>/em totally confused</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Vehementi</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well first of all bladaddy, it would only be critting once every .95 of a second because weapons wait their recharge length before attacking again... and secondly, the point of weapons with insanely low speed is so you can slide your agg/def bar to the left and still be attacking at max speed.<P>But his data is somewhat flawed.<P>-V</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Point</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I don't buy the minimum being 1.0<P>There's quite a few weapons with attack and/or recharge of under 1 second.<P>Use a weapon with a .25 attack and a .70 recharge... totals around 1 second before aggdef and initiatives.<P>Set the aggdef in the neutral/middle position... this would add 0 for the aggdef value.  fire a few times.<P>Now crank it all the way agressive... If the minimum delay is 1.0/1.0 then it should have no effect on the speed of the weapon as it is already at it's minimum right?<P>But it makes a huge difference...<P>so either the minimum isn't 1.0 <BR>or the aggdef in the middle isn't a zero modifier<BR>or the minimum takes effect BEFORE aggdef is added<P>I think the client "seconds" are different from server "seconds" as well... but this is interesting insight regardless.<P>good stuff<P>.&lt;<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Romulus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Does anyone know about NanoC Init? Does that follow the same rule?<P>For instance NT's get programs that are close to 1.0s so if you have high NanoC init does it also cap at 1.0s making it better to use a 3.0s cast time program at higher levels?</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
